oth metaphor and ideal, it influenced psychology, religion, moral philosophy; it affected the writing of history as well as the criticism of literature. Here is a wide-ranging and ably written exploration of this fascinating aspect of Victorian ideas. Bruce Haley looks at developments in personal and public health, and at theories about the relation between medical and psychological disorders. He examines influential conceptions of the healthy man: Carlyle's healthy hero, Spencer's biologically perfect man, Newman's gentleman-Christian, Kingsley's muscular Christian. He describes the development of sports and physical training in nineteenth-century England and their importance in schools and universities. He traces the concept of healthy body and healthy mind in boy's fiction (such as Torn Brown's School Days), self-help literature, and the widely read novels of George Eliot, Wilkie Collins, George Meredith, and Charles Kingsley. All these strands of social history, literature, and philosophy are woven together into a seamless whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEngels. 0aEnglische Literatur. 0aEnglish literature. 0aGezondheid. 0aHealth in literature. 0aHealth. 0aKultur. 0aLetterkunde. 0aLiterature, Modern. 0aLiterature. 0aPhysical Fitness. 0aPhysical education and training in literature. 0aPhysical education and training. 0aPublic health. 0aSanté dans la littérature. 0aSport. 0aÉducation physique dans la littérature. 4aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aPhysical education and training -- Great Britain -- History -- 19th century. 4aPublic health -- Great Britain -- History -- 19th century. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Healthy Living.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G